Headlines.Author: Melodie Warner
Headlines.Headline: Ally Financial's Bank Reviewing Options for Agency Mortgage Servicing Rights Portfolio

PARAGRAPH.#text: Ally Financial Inc.'s banking unit is exploring strategic options for its agency mortgage servicing rights portfolio and its business lending operations. The portfolio had an unpaid principal balance of about $122 billion of mortgage loans in the third quarter. The company said Ally Bank will continue to originate a modest level of high-quality residential jumbo mortgages for its own portfolio through correspondents and wholesale brokers. "Going forward our goal is to focus on our customer-centric deposit activities as well as supporting Ally's auto finance operation," said Ally Bank President and Chief Executive Barbara Yastine.

Headlines.Headline: Ace's 2nd Quarter Sank 45% on Realized Losses; Raises Outlook

PARAGRAPH.#text: Ace Ltd.'s ACE second-quarter profit sank 45% as the insurer booked heavy realized losses, masking a rise in premiums written. The company raised its outlook for operating income to a range of $7.20 to $7.60 a share, up from its April view of $7.03 to $7.43, reflecting reserve development and lower-than-planned catastrophe losses. This includes the negative impacts of droughts across the U.S., which are expected to impact its crop insurance business. Like other global insurers, Ace faced heavy catastrophe losses in 2011, due to devastating natural disasters in Japan and New Zealand, and a tough storm season in the U.S.

Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Erik Holm
Headlines.Headline: For Reinsurers, Size Matters In Fight To Acquire Transatlantic

PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--The fight over Transatlantic Holdings Inc. TRH is a battle for size, as reinsurance companies struggle to distinguish themselves from a crowded field. Both Allied World Assurance Co. AWH, which struck a deal to merge with Transatlantic in June, and Validus Holdings Ltd., which made an unsolicited rival bid Tuesday night, could roughly double in size and move into more-elite ranks of the reinsurance world if they successfully pull off a deal with Transatlantic. The winner of the fight would diversify its business by bolting on Transatlantic's global casualty-reinsurance operations, increasing its geographic footprint.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: For Reinsurers, Size Matters In Fight To Acquire Transatlantic

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Ace Ltd. ACE named Vice Chairman John Keogh to the additional role of chief operating officer where he will oversee all property and casualty operations as Brian Dowd retires from full-time work. Dowd, who is currently chairman of North America insurance, will join the office of the chairman July 1 on a part-time basis to focus on underwriting-related matters. Headlines.Headline: Ace Ltd 1Q Profit Down 66% On Higher Catastrophe Losses

PARAGRAPH.#text: Ace Ltd.'s ACE first-quarter profit slid 66% as catastrophe losses jumped sharply, while the company reported net premiums slightly declined. The commercial insurer, which is the holding company for ACE Group, had seen its core earnings improve from a year earlier in the fourth quarter, reversing a streak of declines. But operating earnings declined in the latest quarter and in light of catastrophe losses seen in the first quarter, Ace lowered its full-year outlook. Ace now sees full-year operating income of $5.40 to $5.70 a share, down from the February target of $6.10 to $6.50.

Headlines.Author: Katy Burne
Headlines.Headline: ACE INA Sells $700M 5Yr Bonds At Tsys +108BPs -Source

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds final deal pricing.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Insurer ACE INA Holdings Inc. sold $700 million of five-year bonds Thursday at a discount to yield 2.62%, or 108 basis points over comparable Treasury securities. Earlier price guidance was in the area of 110 basis points over Treasurys and the sale had been increased by $200 million on demand, according to people familiar with the deal. The senior unsecured notes will be fully and unconditionally guaranteed by parent company ACE Ltd. ACE. Deutsche Bank, Morgan Stanley and Wells Fargo Securities led the sale, proceeds of which will be used for general corporate purposes and to repay debt, including part of a $450 million five-year term loan maturing in April 2013 and a $155 million five-year term loan maturing in December 2010, according to a regulatory filing.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: ACE INA Sells $700M 5Yr Bonds At Tsys +108BPs -Source

Headlines.Author: Jessica Papini
Headlines.Headline: Chile Earthquake Insured Losses May Top $8B

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Monday.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Insured losses from a devastating earthquake in Chile could exceed $8 billion, a level that probably won't have a big impact on reinsurers or the pricing of insurance. Chile's well-developed economy and reliance on private insurance coverage will aid in its recovery, unlike some other emerging markets that have been through devastating natural disasters. Catastrophe risk modeling firm, Eqecat Inc., estimated that insured losses from the 8.8 magnitude earthquake that hit Chile Saturday could range from $3 billion to $8 billion, or 25% of the total economic losses.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Chile Earthquake Insured Losses May Top $8B

PARAGRAPH.#text: Property and casualty insurers paid less for reinsurance as they renewed coverage on Jan. 1, thanks to fewer catastrophes than expected and an ample supply of capacity. But the price cuts add up to only a "marginal positive" for most property/casualty insurers, who face soft prices and diminished demand for their own products, said Vinay Misquith, an analyst with Credit Suisse. Property/casualty insurers and reinsurers have generally come through the financial crisis better than other financial institutions, though persistently low interest rates have reduced their investment income.

PARAGRAPH.#text: TAKING THE PULSE: Most of the U.S. was spared damage from major storms this summer, which will help boost third-quarter earnings for property/casualty insurers. Investment results will also be "respectable" following the rise in markets during the quarter, says Sandler O'Neill & Partners analyst Paul Newsome in a recent note. Eqecat Inc., a subsidiary of ABSG Consulting Inc., a risk modeling company that specializes in extreme risk, estimated Monday that personal and commercial insured losses on the coast would total between $6 billion and $10 billion, not including losses to off-shore energy producers, said Eqecat senior vice president Tom Larsen.
